					<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Orthodox rabbinic title, especially in Hasidism</div>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1033289096">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}</style><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article is about the social functions of Hasidic leadership. For the Hasidic theory of leadership, see <a href="/wiki/Tzadik" title="Tzadik">Tzadik</a>. For Menachem Mendel Schneerson (commonly referred to as The Rebbe), see <a href="/wiki/Menachem_Mendel_Schneerson" title="Menachem Mendel Schneerson">Menachem Mendel Schneerson</a>. For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Rebbe_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="Rebbe (disambiguation)">Rebbe (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be confused with <a href="/wiki/Rabbi" title="Rabbi">Rabbi</a>.</div>
